# Cloudflare Wrangler (templates)

## Environments (prod-only policy)

- Maintain **one** production config per Worker: `wrangler.prod.toml` or `wrangler.prod.jsonc`.
- Pin `account_id` in every prod config.
- **Do not** add `wrangler.dev.toml` / `wrangler.stg.toml` or non-prod deploy workflows.
- Local development: `wrangler dev -c wrangler.prod.toml --local` and `wrangler d1 migrations apply … --local -c wrangler.prod.toml`.
- Production deploy: **CI only** (`preflight-cloudflare.mjs` before `wrangler deploy`).

## Compatibility

Keep `compatibility_date` intentional; bump when adopting new runtime APIs.

## Bindings

- Use descriptive binding keys: `DB`, `KV_SESSION`, `R2_FILES`, `QUEUE_EMAIL`, etc.
- Document placeholder IDs (`REPLACE_WITH_*`) until real resources exist.

## Naming

- Align Worker **name** with `<org>-<product>-<resource>-<domain>-prod` (or org standard with `-prod` suffix).
- Queue and binding resource names use `-prod` suffix in production.

## Queues

- Match **queue names** between producers and consumers across services.

## Secrets

- Never commit secrets. Use Wrangler secrets / CI OIDC and `.env` locally from `.env.example` only.
- **Never use `wrangler login` (OAuth)** for org/product work. Use `CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN` + `CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID` via direnv (`~/.config/<org>/cloudflare.env`). See **`15-org-account-isolation.mdc`**.
- Production `wrangler secret put`: **CI only**.

## Cleanup

Non-prod Cloudflare resources are retired. See `docs/runbooks/worker-cleanup.md` in labs-core.
